These numbers have swung around a lot over the last two years which makes it hard to have any certainty. We haven't been below 6m since 2016 except at the beginning of the pandemic so numbers that low might imply a new economic crisis (far from impossible). On the other hand, we have only seen 8-9m one month in the last 20 years, and only ever 10m+ the last 3 months. So most likely outcome is some kind of return to baseline centered around 6-8m. Numbers as high as July/Aug 2021 are historically unprecedented and likely not sustainable given that a hiring crunch will eventually lead to a business slowdown if the cost of labor is too high

Pre-pandemic it looked like the job openings number might have begun to plateau after a long rise [1]. That corresponded to an unemployment rate of about 3.6% at the time [2]. Economists like to talk about "full employment" which is basically where everyone who wants to work is working [3]. When that happens there's still unemployment, but a more natural rate corresponding to people who are switching jobs or who have lost their job and are working on finding a new one. Looking at [1], recessions cause job openings to plummet as businesses don't want to pay the costs to hire more employees, and that coincides with a rising unemployment rate in [2]. So if history and late 2019 is any guide, the unemployment rate corresponding to us getting sort of close to full employment is probably somewhere around 3 to 4%.
